nd, United Kingdom":"Thirsk, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","North Rode, Cheshire, England":"North Rode, Cheshire, England","Chester, Cheshire West and Chester district, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chester, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1250–1310":"1250–1310","1253–Female":"1253–Deceased","1255–Female":"1255–Deceased","1274–1305":"1274–1305","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1230–1304":"1230–1304","1234–Female":"1234–Deceased","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1234":"1234","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","Abt 1275":"about 1275","Sowerby, Hambleton district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Thirsk, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","North Rode, Cheshire, England":"North Rode, Cheshire, England","Chester, Cheshire West and Chester district, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chester, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rode","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Erwin, Ewald, Hans, Heinz, Oskar, Viktor, Claus, Frieda, Fritz, Gerhard, Horst.","German and French: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’. Compare   Robert  ,   Rudiger  .","North German, Danish, and English: topographic name for someone who lived on land cleared for cultivation or in a clearing in woodland, from Middle Low German <i>rode</i>, Danish <i>rothe</i>, Old English <i>rod</i>. There are a number of places in England named with this word, for example Rode in Cheshire, and the surname may derive from any of these. Compare   Rhode  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ruth","meanings":["German: from a short form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names formed with <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ (see   Rode  ).","(<b>Rüth</b>): habitational name from a place so named near Euskirchen in Rhineland.","English: from Middle English <i>reuth(e)</i> ‘pity’, a nickname perhaps for a charitable person or for a pitiable one. The personal name <i>Ruth</i> was little used in England in the Middle Ages among non-Jews, and is unlikely to have had any influence on the surname."]},{"name":"Rody","meanings":["German: variant of   Rode   1.","Scottish: variant of <b>Rodie</b>, from a pet form of   Roderick  ."]},{"name":"Robert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Gilles, Normand, Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Michel, Edouard, Gaston, Yves.","French, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Rodeman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Rodemann</b>:","topographic name for someone who lived on woodland cleared for cultivation, a variant of   Rode   2 with the addition of Middle Low German <i>man</i> ‘man’.","from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Hrodman</i>, formed with <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown, fame’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Winterroth","meanings":["German: topographic name for someone who lived on the north side of a clearing (see   Rode  )."]},{"name":"Roth","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a person with red hair, from Middle High German <i>rōt</i>, German <i>rot</i> ‘red’. As a Jewish name it is at least in part artificial: its frequency as a Jewish surname is disproportionate to the number of Jews who, one may reasonably assume, were red-headed during the period of surname adoption. This form of the German surname (especially in this sense and in the sense 2 below) is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), where it is most common, and in some other European countries, e.g. Czechia and Croatia.","German and English (Middlesex): topographic name for someone who lived on land that had been cleared, from Old High German <i>rod</i>, Middle English <i>roth(e)</i> (Old English <i>roth</i>) ‘clearing’. In England, the name may also be a habitational name from any of the places like Rothend in Ashdon (Essex), Roe End in Markyate (Hertfordshire), Roe Green in Hatfield (Hertfordshire), or Roe Green in Sandon (Hertfordshire).","German: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’. Compare   Rode   1,   Ross   4."]},{"name":"Rohde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Kurt, Otto, Bernd, Hans, Heino, Heinz, Ewald, Gerhard, Helmut, Hermann, Klaus.","German and Danish: variant of   Rode   2 and a habitational name from any of various places called Rohde or Rohden in Lower Saxony, Saxony, Westphalia, and Hesse. Compare   Rhode   and   Rhody  ."]},{"name":"Roady","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Rode  ."]},{"name":"Rodich","meanings":["Americanized form of Serbian and Croatian <b>Rodić</b>: patronymic from a short form of a Slavic compound personal name based on the element <i>rod</i> ‘family, relatives’, e.g. <i>Rodoslav</i>.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rodič</b>: surname probably related to (or derived from)   Rode  . Alternatively, it may be of the same origin as the Serbian and Croatian name above.","German: perhaps a variant of <b>Rohdich</b>, from a personal name based on ancient Germanic <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown, victory’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Knight Robert de Rode was born in 1250, in North Rode, Cheshire, England, his father, William de Rode, was 20 and his mother, Eva Watton, was 16. He married Mathilda De Watton in 1274, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1310, in Thirsk, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1250–1310":"1250–1310","1253–Female":"1253–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1274–1305":"1274–1305","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1230–1304":"1230–1304","1234–Female":"1234–Surnud","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1234":"1234","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","Abt 1275":"umbes 1275","Sowerby, Hambleton district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Thirsk, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Rode, Cheshire, England":"North Rode, Cheshire, England","Chester, Cheshire West and Chester district, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chester, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1250–1310":"1250–1310","1253–Female":"1253–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1274–1305":"1274–1305","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1230–1304":"1230–1304","1234–Female":"1234–Kuollut","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1274":